  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony crime in the United States and in many other jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (such as from drug trafficking, terrorism, or other criminal activities) appear legal by concealing their true origin. The specific laws and penalties for money laundering vary by country and jurisdiction, but in the U.S., it is governed by federal and state laws.\n\nUnder U.S. federal law, the **Money Laundering Control Act (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957)** makes it a crime to knowingly engage in financial transactions involving the proceeds of unlawful activity. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Fines**: Up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.\n- **Imprisonment**: Up to 20 years in federal prison for each offense.\n- **Civil penalties**: Additional fines and asset forfeiture.\n\nIn addition to federal laws, many states have their own money laundering statutes, which can also impose significant penalties. Repeat offenders or those involved in large-scale laundering operations often face harsher sentences.\n\nMoney laundering is taken very seriously because it enables criminal activity, undermines financial systems, and can facilitate terrorism, corruption, and other serious crimes. If you are facing charges or have questions about money laundering, it is essential to consult a qualified attorney for legal advice.",
